<font color="#FF0000">TO MY FRIEND</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug 15 18:02:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward Humming Eagle,<br><br>
It is I who have offended you, and I am sorry. I mean no contempt towards anyone. I show my respect for the sanctity of this thread by leaving out the politics of the war.<br><br>
The thread started by Chet Botkins (in which I posted the reference to &quot;warrior&quot;) contains a very familiar theme among Vietnam veterans, REMF *Versus* combat vets. This is not the way it should be. There should be no competition. Only respect.<br><br>
I would gladly accept the status of &quot;warrior&quot; if it means a person who never ever gives up. I have fought for everything that I have achieved in life, without complaint. I know what it is to swallow pride, also. I look at those uncomfortable experiences as milestones of manhood. Sometimes the proper thing to do is to keep silent. It is not easy.<br><br>
What I gathered from the term &quot;warrior&quot;, in the REMF vs Combat vet context, was that those who were not involved with combat operations were not entitled to consider themselves warriors. I think that is the spirit of what Chet was saying. So, rather than leave any who served in Vietnam behind, I preferred to renounce my status as a warrior. We do not leave others &quot;behind on the battlefield&quot;.<br><br>
Your subsequent words have enlightened me. Thanks.<br><br>
Leaving our precious families and homelives for the unknown fate of the combat zone is something that every person who served in Vietnam can remember. It is an awful feeling: not knowing if we will see our loved one's faces again. We ALL experienced that sinking feeling as we boarded the plane. That is what makes all of us EQUAL. That is how it should be.<br><br>

<p><code>-- nospamwingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


